    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Content freshness</strong> is how current, updated, and relevant a webpage is. Google uses it as a ranking factor for time-sensitive and rapidly evolving topics — activated by the Query Deserves Freshness (QDF) algorithm. Freshness combines publication date, last-modification date, update frequency, and the substance of the changes made.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Queries affected</div>
            <div class="tms-value">~33% (QDF)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Content</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Fresh-page rank lift</div>
            <div class="tms-value">1.5x on time-sensitive queries</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Fresh does not automatically mean recent. Google's freshness algorithm rewards pages that are actually more current — better data, updated screenshots, added sections — not pages that swapped a year in the title. The difference between the two is what separates the sites that keep ranking from the sites that don't.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is content freshness?</h2>
        <p>Content freshness is the state of being current. For SEO purposes it is a combination of five inputs Google evaluates:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Original publication date</strong> — when the page first went live.</li>
          <li><strong>Last modification timestamp</strong> — most recent substantive update.</li>
          <li><strong>Update frequency pattern</strong> — how often the page changes over time.</li>
          <li><strong>Scope of changes made</strong> — a typo fix is not the same as a full data refresh.</li>
          <li><strong>Freshness demand of the query</strong> — some queries need fresh answers; some don't.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Freshness matters most for time-sensitive queries — anything with words like "2026," "latest," "news," or "today," and any topic where information changes quickly (technology, finance, medicine, legal). It matters least for evergreen queries — foundational how-tos, definitions, historical facts.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's Query Deserves Freshness (QDF)</div>
          <p>Introduced in 2007 and updated repeatedly since, QDF is Google's mechanism for deciding when freshness should influence ranking. Roughly <strong>33% of searches</strong> get freshness weighting; the other 67% don't. Time-sensitive terms and news queries always do.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why content freshness matters for rankings</h2>
        <p>Freshness is not a top-3 ranking factor for every query, but for the queries that qualify, it's decisive. Five ways it moves rankings and revenue:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>QDF weighting.</strong> On roughly 1 in 3 queries, fresher content ranks above older content of similar quality.</li>
          <li><strong>Time-sensitive rank lift.</strong> Pages updated within the last 6 months rank 1.5x higher on time-sensitive queries.</li>
          <li><strong>60% of marketers cite refreshing as their top SEO tactic.</strong> Semrush and HubSpot surveys consistently rank content refresh above net-new publishing for ROI.</li>
          <li><strong>Signal to AI Overviews.</strong> AI-generated summaries prefer sources with recent <code>dateModified</code> — freshness increases citation rate.</li>
          <li><strong>User trust.</strong> A visible "Updated April 2026" line increases dwell time and conversion — humans read it before Google's crawlers do.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Google measures content freshness</h2>
        <p>Google combines on-page signals, structured data, and inferred signals from crawl behavior.</p>
        <h3>1. On-page dates</h3>
        <p>Visible publication and last-updated timestamps in the byline area. Google reads these; users read them too.</p>
        <h3>2. Structured data</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># JSON-LD schema in the head</span><br>
          &#123;<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="uf-label">"@type":</span> <span class="uf-new">"Article"</span>,<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="uf-label">"datePublished":</span> <span class="uf-new">"2024-03-12"</span>,<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="uf-label">"dateModified":</span> <span class="uf-new">"2026-06-14"</span><br>
          &#125;
        </div>
        <h3>3. Crawl-based signals</h3>
        <p>Google detects the amount of content that actually changed between crawls. Cosmetic edits (typo fixes, sidebar updates) count for less than substantial rewrites.</p>
        <h3>4. Freshness demand per query</h3>
        <p>Google's own SERP behavior gives it a signal — if searchers frequently click older results and leave (pogo-stick to Google), fresh content is expected. If they read older results happily, freshness matters less.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Where freshness matters most (and least)</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Content type</th><th>Freshness weight</th><th>Recommended update cadence</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>News + breaking events</strong></td><td>Extreme</td><td>Continuously</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Product reviews + tech</strong></td><td>High</td><td>Every 3-6 months</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Finance, pricing, tax</strong></td><td>High</td><td>Every 3-6 months</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Medical + legal</strong></td><td>High</td><td>Annual + on regulation change</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Statistics + industry data</strong></td><td>Medium-High</td><td>Annual with fresh sources</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Evergreen how-tos</strong></td><td>Low</td><td>Every 18-24 months</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Foundational definitions</strong></td><td>Very low</td><td>Only if the concept changes</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real content freshness examples</h2>
        <h3>1. SaaS pricing page refresh</h3>
        <p>A SaaS blog compared "Top 10 CRM tools 2024." Traffic peaked at 8k monthly visits, then decayed as competitors published 2025 and 2026 versions. Rewriting the intro, updating every product's pricing and feature list, and adding new tools brought traffic back to 11k within 60 days.</p>
        <h3>2. Accounting firm tax guide</h3>
        <p>Blog post on "small business tax deductions" fell from #3 to #14 in one year. Refreshing every dollar figure, updating deduction limits for the new tax year, and adding a downloadable checklist restored the page to #2 in 12 weeks — outranking its original position.</p>
        <h3>3. Ecommerce category page</h3>
        <p>A gear retailer's category page ranked #5 for their bread-and-butter query. Adding a "Updated April 2026" ribbon plus 3 new "best of 2026" product entries lifted click-through rate 22% — the ranking didn't change, but the CTR did, delivering more traffic from the same slot.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Content freshness vs. content decay — related concepts</h2>
        <p>Freshness is the state; decay is what happens when the state fades.</p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Content freshness</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>A quality signal Google reads</li>
              <li>Combines dates, changes, and update cadence</li>
              <li>Improved by substantive edits</li>
              <li>Rewards intent + evidence, not just timestamps</li>
              <li>Actionable via refresh playbook</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4><a href="/glossary/content-decay/">Content decay</a></h4>
            <ul>
              <li>The process of losing rankings over time</li>
              <li>Diagnosis: click decline in Search Console</li>
              <li>Caused by stale content, new competitors, algorithm shifts</li>
              <li>Reversed by improving freshness</li>
              <li>Actionable via refresh + republish</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 content freshness best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Update high-traffic pages quarterly.</strong> Prioritize by revenue impact; a page driving 5,000 clicks is worth 10 pages driving 500 each.</li>
          <li><strong>Show both dates on the page.</strong> "Published Aug 2024 · Updated April 2026" — visible to users, visible to Google.</li>
          <li><strong>Implement freshness schema correctly.</strong> <code>datePublished</code> and <code>dateModified</code> in JSON-LD, matching the visible dates.</li>
          <li><strong>Add year modifiers only when it makes sense.</strong> "Best CRMs for 2026" for annual roundups; not for evergreen how-tos.</li>
          <li><strong>Republish with substantive changes.</strong> Rule of thumb: change 30%+ of the content before updating the modified date.</li>
          <li><strong>Redirect or noindex obsolete content.</strong> Old-year pages that no longer serve queries either 301 to the fresh version or get noindexed.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — date manipulation without content change</div>
          <p>Bumping the <code>dateModified</code> to today without actually changing the content is one of the tactics Google explicitly names as manipulation in its <a href="/glossary/search-quality-rater-guidelines/">Quality Rater Guidelines</a>. Detected patterns can result in freshness signals being ignored — or worse, quality demotion.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common content freshness mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Over-refreshing evergreen content.</strong> Constantly editing a stable definition page can destabilize its rankings.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring the internal linking around a refreshed page.</strong> New content sections need new outbound and inbound internal links.</li>
          <li><strong>Removing the original publication date.</strong> Removing history makes both users and Google suspicious.</li>
          <li><strong>Refreshing without validating decay.</strong> Some traffic drops come from query volume decline, not freshness — refresh won't fix those.</li>
          <li><strong>Only refreshing the intro and dates.</strong> Google rewards depth of change. Update stats, examples, screenshots, FAQ, and internal links together.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">How often does Google prefer fresh content?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Google's Query Deserves Freshness algorithm activates for roughly 33% of searches. Time-modifier queries (2026, latest, news) and fast-evolving topics like tech or medicine always get freshness weighting.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
