            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No — Google explicitly detects and demotes date manipulation. Freshness signals require actual content change: new data, added sections, updated screenshots. Change 30%+ of the content when updating the dateModified field.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">How do I tell Google a page has been updated?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Show a visible last-updated date and include datePublished and dateModified in JSON-LD schema. Google reads both, and both must match reality.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">How often should I refresh content?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Time-sensitive topics: every 3-6 months. Most B2B and industry content: every 12 months. Evergreen how-tos: every 18-24 months, or when a competitor overtakes you in the SERP.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">What is the difference between content freshness and content decay?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Freshness is the state (how current the page is). Decay is the process (the page losing rankings as freshness fades). You improve freshness to reverse decay.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

